review_blob: First Guinness! First appearances are amazing, to watch the head form (poured from can). Absolutely opaque black, head with tight beading, colour of milk coffee. First reaction to taste was a thinness?, probably actually the low carbonation. The dark malt character is very light on the palate, making this a far lighter flavour impact than I expected. Can understand how this could be drunk all day.

Enjoyable delicate soma for this style. Colour a clear dark black beer with a decent cappuccino coloured head that becomes a light topping. Lighter flaps but a clear burnt toffee/light coffee character. Drink again.
Japanese porter. Very black, dark head. Light taroma, flavour. Low carbonation. Apparently an American style porter.

Tasted this somewhat hastily but enjoyed it enough to warrant another try. Reminded me of Weihenstephaner Hefeweizen, which is a good sign. Similar phenol characters, similar light cloudiness (more sediment - roll it next time?), strong head.
Enjoyable richly flavoured porter. Dark colour, light had, coffee tones without any burnt characters. Clan palate. Yum, try more.

Aroma dominated by burnt malt toffee character. Great black opaque colour topped by good creamy lasting head. Taste is dominated by black beer burnt character. Palate is clean with some residual burnt malt at back of mouth that dissipates quickly. Overall a pleasant black beer, but not much of the hops advertised in IPA name. Possibly a little too much of burnt character without a lot of other depth of flavour.

Light fragrance with a caramel toastiness. Golden to deep brown colour with some cloudiness, light ringing of bead around glass is only head. Bitterness is first reaction in mouth, leaving a slightly puckered feeling but clean of the palate. A residual floral hop character.

Really enjoyed this very malty ale. Dont know what an English Red Ale should be like, but this is certainly to my taste. Lovely rich toffee malt, with something extra I found hard to define, perhaps a smokiness. Could regularly drink this in late autumn and into winter. Would go well with richly flavoured/sauced foods.

Loved this. Admittedly one of my first American style IPAs, but really enjoy what the additional malt gives to the body. The hops have a summery freshness, will have to try another and see what I think off how the dry hopping lingers on the palate.

Trappistes Rochefort was my first introduction to Abbey ales. Love its creamy full head, rich maltiness and yeast characters. When tasting this 6 it doesnt seem to have the balance I remember from the 8 and 10. Had wasnt as strong either and Im noticing the colour its a little muddy rather than cloudy. All the same, love it!

Really enjoyed this as one of my first tripels. The triple malt provides a rich tasty flavor that I enjoyed, yet very much in balance. Clean palate without any particular character lingering. Definitely try again. Look out for 8% alcohol, excellent for winter.

These are personal notes - Im new to this and not familiar with the style. I rolled this beer before tasColor is a rich chocolate brown with a fair amount of cloudiness, quick to a large short-lived head. . Flavor is what really packs a punch, as you would expect from its appearance. This bottle has an overpowering medicinal taste as it first hits the mouth - too much so for me (I know this is a characteristic of this style). Later the mouth is left with a rich taste and clean palate.

Color is a clear Amber gold, with a fine white long-lasting head. Aroma has an attractive sweetness, my best deScription is green. Flavor has a bitterness that provides a fine contrast to the sweet aroma. Bitterness lasts on the palate, providing a good accompaniment to strongly flavored foods, perhaps Indian curry or Asian.
beer_name: Bridge Road Single Hop IPA: Ella

review_blob: Appealing deep malty brown color, light tight head. Light malty aroma followed through in the mouth. Enjoyable malty flavor, somewhat nutty. Im enjoying it in an Australian summer, would bee equally enjoyable in winter.
